    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-09T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-09T22:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8702: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-10T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 10, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>259. Our 258, July 10, 10 a.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Hidaka last night told an American news correspondent that the Central
                        News Agency account of his yesterday afternoon’s interview with Chen Chieh
                        was not strictly accurate. He said that, (1) the Foreign Office had not
                        actually lodged a protest with the Embassy July 8 but merely requested that
                        steps be taken to cause cessation of hostilities; (2) yesterday he himself
                        made no protest and told Chen that he did not wish to and would not do so
                        unless the Chinese protested; (3) if the War Office protests were not filed
                        the incident could be localized and not become an issue between the two
                        Governments; and, (4) it was the desire of the Japanese Government that it
                        be settled amicably by officials in the North as a local matter.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>To the Department, Peiping, Tokyo. By mail to Shanghai.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
